      ],
      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Welcome to this course on AI in humanitarian aid distribution. At first glance, using artificial intelligence to help deliver food, shelter, and medical care to people in crisis sounds like a genuinely good idea. These systems can process enormous amounts of data very quickly, helping organisations decide who needs help most urgently and how to allocate limited resources across large populations. But here is where things get complicated. The data these systems rely on is not always complete or accurate, and when it is flawed, the consequences can be serious. People who are already the most vulnerable, those hardest to reach or least visible in the data, can quietly fall through the gaps. And importantly, just because a decision is made by an algorithm does not mean it is fair or neutral. Throughout this course, we will explore how these systems work, where they can go wrong, and what that means for real people in some of the world's most difficult situations."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "When we talk about using AI to distribute aid, one of the biggest problems we face is the quality of the data we feed into these systems. If the records used to train an AI are incomplete or outdated, entire communities can simply be overlooked. And here is the difficult part: a lot of historical data already reflects old inequalities. It was collected in ways that left out women, displaced persons, and minority groups, because they were never properly counted in official registries to begin with. So when an AI learns from that data, it does not learn about current needs, it learns about past blind spots. What makes this especially serious is that even a small gap in the data does not stay small. Over time, those gaps compound, and the result is a system that consistently sends resources to the wrong places while the most vulnerable people receive little or nothing at all."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "One of the biggest challenges in humanitarian aid is something that might not be immediately obvious: the data simply isn't complete. When people are displaced, they often don't have official documents, passports, ID cards, or registration papers. And if you don't exist in a system, you can't receive support from it. It's as straightforward, and as troubling, as that. This problem is made worse in informal settlements or hard to reach rural areas, where populations are frequently undercounted or missed altogether. Add to that language barriers and low literacy levels, which can prevent people from registering in the first place, and you start to see how the gaps build up. The really important point here is that these aren't just minor technical oversights. Even a small gap in the data can mean an entire community receives nothing. So before we can talk about how AI helps, we need to understand what it's working with, and what it isn't."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "Now, one of the most serious challenges with AI systems is the quality of the data they learn from. If that data is flawed or incomplete, the AI will make flawed decisions, and in humanitarian work, that has real consequences for real people. For example, if a system is trained mostly on data from past crises, it may not recognise the patterns of a brand new emergency. Rural communities are often poorly documented, so they can be overlooked entirely. There are also significant gender gaps in how needs are recorded, which means women and girls may not receive the support they actually require. And refugee populations, who are frequently on the move and difficult to track, often have incomplete records in these systems. The core principle here is simple: biased input produces biased output. The AI can only work with what it is given, so if the data does not reflect everyone equally, neither will the help that gets distributed."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "One of the most important challenges we face when using AI in humanitarian work is bias. If the data we feed into an AI system is skewed or incomplete, the system will make unfair decisions, and that can mean vulnerable people miss out on the help they desperately need. Minority groups and marginalised communities are often underrepresented in datasets, which makes this problem even more serious. So what can we do about it? First, we need to regularly audit our data sources, checking where the information comes from and who might be missing from it. Second, and this is really valuable, we need diverse teams working on these systems. When people with different backgrounds and lived experiences are involved, they are far more likely to spot gaps and blind spots that others might overlook. The bottom line is straightforward: if we invest in better, more representative data, we build fairer AI systems, and fairer systems mean more equitable aid for everyone who needs it."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "One of the most important things we need to talk about when using AI in humanitarian work is bias. If the data we feed into an AI system reflects historical inequalities, the system will simply reproduce those inequalities, and that means the people who are already most vulnerable can end up being overlooked or underserved. So what can we do about it? First, we need to regularly audit where our data is coming from and ask honest questions about who might be missing from it. Second, and this is really crucial, we need diverse teams involved in building and reviewing these systems. People with different backgrounds and lived experiences are far more likely to spot gaps that others might miss. And finally, before any AI tool is rolled out in the field, it must be properly tested to check for unfair outcomes. Getting this right is not just a technical task, it is an ethical responsibility."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "Bias in AI systems is one of the most serious challenges we face in humanitarian work, because unfair outcomes can mean the wrong people receive help, or vulnerable groups are overlooked entirely. So how do we tackle this? It starts with looking closely at your data. Are there gaps? Are certain communities underrepresented? If so, your AI will likely reflect those gaps in its decisions. From there, it is really important to bring in diverse local voices, people who understand the communities being served, because they will spot problems that outsiders simply miss. Once your system is running, test how it performs across different groups, not just on average. If one group is consistently receiving worse outcomes, something needs to change. That might mean going back and correcting skewed training data. And importantly, this is not a one-time fix. You need to keep monitoring results on an ongoing basis, because bias can creep back in as circumstances change."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So let's bring together the key lessons from this section. The most important thing to understand is that AI is only as good as the data you feed it. If that data is flawed, incomplete, or biased, the system will reflect those problems, and in humanitarian work, that can mean real people not receiving the help they need. It is worth asking yourself, every time you use an AI tool: where does this data come from, how current is it, and who might be missing from it? The communities most at risk are often the least visible in datasets, and even small gaps can grow into serious consequences when decisions are made at scale. So here is something practical to try before the next lesson. Pick one data source your organisation relies on and take a close look at it. Ask whether it is truly complete, and whether any groups might be underrepresented. That kind of critical thinking is where good AI use begins."
        }
      ]
    }
